Day 6 code
<!doctype html>
<html>
<head>
<style>
.tab-btn {
padding: 10px 20px;
border: none;
cursor: pointer;
background: #eee;
}
.tab-btn.active {
background: #4facfe;
color: white;
}
.panel {
display: none;
padding: 20px;
border: 1px solid #ddd;
}
.panel.active {
display: block;
}
</style>
</head>
<body>
<div id="tabs">
<button class="tab-btn active" data-target="panel1">Introduction</button>
<button class="tab-btn" data-target="panel2">Price</button>
<button class="tab-btn" data-target="panel3">Comment</button>
</div>
<div id="panel1" class="panel active">Intro Content</div>
<div id="panel2" class="panel">Price Content</div>
<div id="panel3" class="panel">Comment Content</div> <script>
document.getElementById("tabs").addEventListener("click", (e) => {
if (!e.target.classList.contains("tab-btn")) return;
document.querySelectorAll(".tab-btn, .panel").forEach((el) => {
el.classList.remove("active");
});
e.target.classList.add("active");
const targetId = e.target.dataset.target;
document.getElementById(targetId).classList.add("active");
});
</script>
</body>
</html>
This code creates a tab interface with three buttons — Introduction, Price, and Comment — and displays only the content panel connected to the selected button. When a button is clicked, JavaScript uses event delegation on the tabs container, removes the active class from all buttons and panels, and then adds it to the clicked button. Finally, the button’s data-target value identifies the matching panel, while CSS uses the active class to highlight the selected button and show its content.
