2/ CSS elements
<style>
.tab-btn {
padding: 10px 20px;
border: none;
cursor: pointer;
background: #eee;
}
.tab-btn.active {
background: #4facfe;
color: white;
}
.panel {
display: none;
padding: 20px;
border: 1px solid #ddd;
}
.panel.active {
display: block;
}
</style>Class selectors are used to apply CSS styles to the HTML elements with the tab-btn and panel classes in the <body>, as well as to change their appearance or visibility when they also have the active class. Specifically, .tab-btn styles every tab button, .panel hides every content panel by default, .tab-btn.active highlights the selected button, and .panel.active displays the selected panel.
3/ JS method with DOM

<body> <div id="tabs">
<button class="tab-btn active" data-target="panel1">Introduction</button>
<button class="tab-btn" data-target="panel2">Price</button>
<button class="tab-btn" data-target="panel3">Comment</button>
</div>
<div id="panel1" class="panel active">Intro Content</div>
<div id="panel2" class="panel">Price Content</div>
<div id="panel3" class="panel">Comment Content</div>
<script>
document.getElementById("tabs").addEventListener("click", (e) => {
if (!e.target.classList.contains("tab-btn")) return;
document.querySelectorAll(".tab-btn, .panel").forEach((el) => {
el.classList.remove("active");
});
e.target.classList.add("active");
const targetId = e.target.dataset.target;
document.getElementById(targetId).classList.add("active");
});
</script>
</body>
A click event listener is added to the tabs container. When a click occurs, the code checks whether the exact element clicked has the tab-btn class; if it does not, the function stops and nothing else happens. If it does, the code selects all tab buttons and content panels and removes their active class. It then adds the active class to the clicked button, causing the active CSS styling to be applied. Next, it reads the clicked button’s data-target value and stores it in targetId. Finally, it uses that value to find the corresponding panel by its id and adds the active class, making the panel visible.
Note:
e.target.dataset.target reads the value of the data-target attribute from the exact HTML element that was clicked.
